%N A394369 a(n) is the unique integral median length of the triangle (A394368(n), A394367(n), A394366(n)).
%C A394369 If the medians to two distinct sides of an integer triangle were integral, then parity in 4*m^2 = 2*y^2 + 2*z^2 - x^2 would force x, y, z to be even. Under the gcd condition this would lead to infinite 2-adic descent unless the two medians coincided. Hence at most one distinct integral median length can occur (in the isosceles case two medians may exist geometrically, but they are equal).
%H A394369 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394369/b394369.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10098</a>
%e A394369 4 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (5, 5, 6) the median to z = 6 has length m = 4. It splits z into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A394369 7 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (7, 8, 9) the median to y = 8 has length m = 7. It splits y into 4 and 4, yielding triangles (4, 7, 7) and (4, 7, 9), and gcd(7, 8, 9, 7) = 1.
%e A394369 9 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (8, 14, 14) the medians to y = 14 and z = 14 both have length m = 9. Each splits the side into 7 and 7, yielding triangles (7, 8, 9) and (7, 9, 14), and gcd(8, 14, 14, 9) = 1.
%p A394369 # See Huber link in A394366.
